@page "/facility"

<section class="facility-hero">
    <h1>Our Facility</h1>
    <p>
        Ripple operates a year‑round indoor aquaponics facility designed to grow fresh produce and fish 
        sustainably for the Chicagoland community. Our space is built around efficiency, food safety, 
        and community involvement — all while supporting ongoing research and education.
    </p>
</section>

<section class="facility-section">
    <h2>Facility Layout</h2>
    <p>Our warehouse is divided into three main areas:</p>

    <div class="facility-grid">
        <div class="facility-card">
            <h3>Food Production (70%)</h3>
            <p>
                The heart of Ripple. This area includes tilapia tanks, filtration systems, nutrient‑rich 
                water circulation, multi‑level hydroponic channels, and LED grow lighting for consistent 
                year‑round growth.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="facility-card">
            <h3>Research Area (15%)</h3>
            <p>
                A dedicated space for testing new aquaponic configurations, monitoring water quality, 
                experimenting with plant varieties, and improving system efficiency.
            </p>
        </div>

        <div class="facility-card">
            <h3>Community Garden & Education (15%)</h3>
            <p>
                A hands‑on space where community members can learn aquaponics, students can conduct 
                projects, and volunteers can participate in planting and harvesting.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="facility-section">
    <h2>Biosecurity & Food Safety</h2>
    <p>
        Food safety is our top priority. Our facility includes separate zones for fish, plants, and 
        packaging, strict wash‑in/wash‑out procedures, daily water checks, and automated sensors for 
        pH, temperature, ammonia, and nitrate.
    </p>
</section>

<section class="facility-section">
    <h2>How the System Works</h2>
    <p>
        Ripple uses a <strong>decoupled aquaponics system</strong>, meaning the fish and plant systems 
        can be adjusted independently. This allows better water control, easier harvesting, reduced 
        stress on fish, and more stable plant growth.
    </p>
</section>

<section class="facility-section">
    <h2>Designed for Sustainability</h2>
    <p>
        Our facility includes skylights to reduce energy use, efficient LED lighting, water 
        recirculation, minimal chemical inputs, and a layout designed for long‑term scalability.
    </p>
</section>
